 und behutsam Bezüge zum sozialen Kontext zu erschließen versuchen.  aThe work of the Greek poet Babrios (2nd century CE), a writer of fables in iambic verses akin to the Roman fabulist Phaedrus, is presented here for the first time in a literal German prose translation along with the original text. The stories are partly in the tradition of Aesop, but some of them were the author’s original inventions and play wittily with the genre at a high level of narrative art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aFabel. 4aVerserzählung. 4aÄsoptradition. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAesop tradition.  aFable.  averse translation.1 aHolzberg, Niklas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2019z9783110605945oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311062165540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311062218840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110622188423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110622188.jpg  a978-3-11-071956-7  DG Plus eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2019  aZDB-23-DGGb2019